code.snippet:
// ❌ BAD - missing ref means the increment is lost
struct Inventory { public int Stock; }
void DeductStock(Inventory inv, int qty) { inv.Stock -= qty; } // modifies copy only
Inventory warehouse = new Inventory { Stock = 100 };
DeductStock(warehouse, 10);
Console.WriteLine(warehouse.Stock); // still 100 - bug

// ✅ GOOD - ref lets the method update the caller's value
void DeductStock(ref Inventory inv, int qty) { inv.Stock -= qty; }
DeductStock(ref warehouse, 10);
Console.WriteLine(warehouse.Stock); // 90

q:
Predict the output:
```csharp
struct Point { public int X; }

var list = new List<Point> { new Point { X = 1 } };
list[0].X = 99;
Console.WriteLine(list[0].X);
```

code.snippet:
// ❌ BAD - assigning to a field of a List indexer return value (compile error)
List<Point> points = new List<Point> { new Point { X = 1 } };
points[0].X = 99; // CS1612 - cannot modify the return value of List indexer

// ✅ GOOD - copy out, mutate, copy back
var p = points[0];
p.X = 99;
points[0] = p;
Console.WriteLine(points[0].X); // 99

